The provided sources focus on the grammatical structure and functional usage of modal auxiliaries in English, emphasizing how their precise application enhances communication impact and appropriateness.
Overview of Modal Auxiliaries
Modal auxiliaries are a specific type of auxiliary used to indicate modality, such as likelihood, ability, necessity, or obligation. Unlike tense auxiliaries (e.g., is, are, am), modals are non-tensed and non-inflectional, meaning they do not change form with tense, number, or person (e.g., you cannot add "-ing" or "-es" to "can").
Key Modals and Their Functions
1. Can and Could
•	Ability: "Can" denotes present ability, while "could" denotes past ability. 
o	Example: "I can play tennis" (present) versus "I could play tennis when I was in school" (past).
•	Possibility: "Could" is generally used for specific guesses, while "can" is reserved for general possibilities. 
o	Example: "The bus could be late" (specific guess) versus "Living in New York can cost a fortune" (general truth).
•	Politeness: "Could" is considered more polite and formal than "can" for requests. 
o	Example: "Could I speak to Vaiga, please?".
2. Will and Would
•	Real vs. Imagined: "Will" is used for real situations in the future, whereas "would" is for imagined or hypothetical situations. 
o	Example: "If it rains tomorrow, I will stay home" (likely) versus "If I had a magic wand, I would change history" (imagined).
•	Past Habits: "Would" describes regular actions in the past, but only with action verbs. 
o	Example: "When we lived in the mountains, we would go hiking all the time".
•	Preferences and Opinions: "Would" is used with verbs like love, hate, or prefer, and when giving opinions on uncertain things. 
o	Example: "I would say he is about 40".
3. Must, Shall, and Should
•	Must: Primary indicator of necessity or obligation. 
o	Example: "The fan is not working; it must be a power failure" (necessity/deduction).
•	Shall: Indicates determination, intention, or strong obligation, often in legal contexts. 
o	Example: "The petitioner shall present the evidence...".
•	Should: Conveys requirements, advice, or probability (weak obligation). 
o	Example: "You should prepare well for the learner’s test".
4. May and Might
•	Possibility: Both indicate possibility, but "may" refers to recent/equal possibility, while "might" indicates remote/weaker possibility. 
o	Example: "The delivery may be delayed" (50/50 chance) versus "The Vice Chancellor might come tomorrow" (unlikely).
•	Permission: "May" is used in formal settings to ask for or grant permission. 
o	Example: "May I take a tea break?".
Communicative Softening and Appropriateness
The sources distinguish between accuracy (grammatical correctness) and appropriateness (how language is used in context). "Learning Softening" involves choosing structures that make the speaker sound less abrupt or harsh, thereby increasing communicative impact.
•	Requests and Suggestions: Using indirect structures buys certainty and avoids imposing on the hearer. 
o	Softening Example: Instead of "Meet with me at nine," use "I was wondering if we could meet at nine".
•	Soft Refusals: It is often more impactful to say "no" without using the word "no" to avoid being devastating to the listener. 
o	Refusal Example: Instead of "No, I can't go for tea," use "I have a lot of stuff pending to take care of".
•	Feedback/Correction: Softening criticism helps maintain a positive conversation. 
o	Correction Example: Instead of "You made a mistake," use "It appears to me that calculations do not add up".

